e, and ultimate revival of natural history within the realms of science and public discourse. Ecologist John G. T. Anderson focuses his account on the lives and contributions of an eclectic group of men and women, from John Ray, John Muir, Charles Darwin, and Rachel Carson, who endured remarkable hardships and privations in order to learn more about their surroundings. Written in an engaging narrative style and with an extensive bibliography of primary sources, the book charts the journey of the naturalist’s endeavor from prehistory to the present, underscoring the need for natural history in an era of dynamic environmental change.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aNatural historyxHistory. 0aNaturalistsxHistory. 0aNaturexEssays; TRAVELxSpecial InterestxEcotourism; NATURExReference. 7aNATURE / Animals.2bisacsh  aacademic books.  aancient history.  aanthropology.  aastrobiology and bioscience.  abeginning of study.  abooks for history lovers.  acreation of life.  adarwin.  adevelopment of sciences.  adiscussion books.  aengaging.  aenvironmental change.  aenvironmental conservation protection.  ahistory of science.  ahome school history books.  ahuman civilization.  ahuman history.  ainformative books.  alearning from experts.  anatural history.  anonfiction books.  aphilosophers.  aquarantine reads.  ascience and math.  ascience books.  ascientists.  astart of civilization.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz978052027376440uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052095445840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520954458423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520954458/original  a978-3-11-069042-2  University of California Press Backlist Package 2